Supplemental Lesson on Binding Data

There might be cases where you need to combine similar data (e.g., data with same columns) that were collected across multiple places. In medicine and public health, some clinical trials are multi-site clinical trials that recruit patients across multiple locations.

Figure 1. Cases where you need to bind data.

For example, Eli Lilly is holding multisite clinical trials across 48 locations in multiple states and countries for its next generation GLP-1 medications for diabetes and weight loss: https://clinicaltrials.gov/study/NCT06354660?term=Retatrutide&rank=1

Supplemental Lesson on Binding Data

For the purpose of the next few slides, I am creating these two R objects below in the R envt (I dont expect you to know how to use tribble at all). Just know that two tables are created in R.

site1_data <- tibble::tribble(
       ~patient_name, ~treatment,  ~percent_weight_loss,
      "Baker, John",      "Placebo",   10,
      "Storm, Elise",     "Experimental GLP-1", 21
  )

site2_data <- tibble::tribble(
       ~patient_name, ~treatment,  ~percent_weight_loss,
      "Chao, Ariel",      "Placebo",   14,
      "Cheng, Kevin",     "Placebo", 12,
      "Tam, Mariecel",     "Experimental GLP-1", 25,
      "Claus, Elizabeth",     "Experimental GLP-1", 26
  )

Supplemental Lesson on Binding Data: bind_rows() with imperfect columns

For the purpose of the next few slides, I am creating these two R objects below in the R envt (I dont expect you to know how to use tribble at all). Just know that two tables are created in R.

data1 <- tibble::tribble(
       ~variable1, ~variable2, 
      "Name 1",      "SSN 1",  
      "Name 2",     "SSN 2"
  )

# data2 has an extra column compared to data1
data2 <- tibble::tribble(
       ~variable1, ~variable2, ~diagnosis,
      "Name 3",      "SSN 3", "Hypertension",
      "Name 4",     "SSN 4", "End-stage renal disease"  
  )

Supplemental Lesson on Binding Data

bind_rows() still work fine when there are extra columns in some of the tables or data frames. It will simply assign NA (missing data or blanks) as values.

data3 <- bind_rows(data1, data2)
data3
## # A tibble: 4  3
##   variable1 variable2 diagnosis              
##   <chr>     <chr>     <chr>                  
## 1 Name 1    SSN 1     <NA>                   
## 2 Name 2    SSN 2     <NA>                   
## 3 Name 3    SSN 3     Hypertension           
## 4 Name 4    SSN 4     End-stage renal disease

Note: dplyrs bind_rows() allows you to bind data without 100% alignment on column names. Do note that base R has an equivalent tool rbind() but it requires perfect alignment on column names, so the case we just did is not permitted in rbind(). Some tutorials you might find online might teach you rbind() but again, use bind_rows() is superior given what was just discussed.

mutate with case_when()

For this example, let us create days_data which contains the seven days of the week. Again: I dont expect you to know how to make tables or data frames from scratch at all.

days_data <- data.frame(day = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))
days_data
##         day
## 1    Monday
## 2   Tuesday
## 3 Wednesday
## 4  Thursday
## 5    Friday
## 6  Saturday
## 7    Sunday

Suppose we want to create another variable called day_status to indicate whether or not a day is weekend or weekday.

mutate with case_when()

To create another variable called day_status to indicate whether or not a day is weekend or weekday, we can leverage mutate with case_when():

.tiny[

days_data |>
  mutate(day_status = case_when(
    day == "Monday" ~ "Weekday", 
    day == "Tuesday" ~ "Weekday", 
    day == "Wednesday" ~ "Weekday", 
    day == "Thursday" ~ "Weekday", 
    day == "Friday" ~ "Weekday", 
    day == "Saturday" ~ "Weekend", 
    day == "Sunday" ~ "Weekend")
    )
##         day day_status
## 1    Monday    Weekday
## 2   Tuesday    Weekday
## 3 Wednesday    Weekday
## 4  Thursday    Weekday
## 5    Friday    Weekday
## 6  Saturday    Weekend
## 7    Sunday    Weekend

]

mutate with case_when()

Why teach you this now? Sometimes, the data you work with simply have too many categories or subgroups. Sometimes in statistics, there are sample size concerns when the small subgroups are low in raw counts, so we often group some subcategories as Other.

For those working on their final projects, this is something you might have to do to make analysis more manageable.

mutate with case_when()

Another example using student_grades. Suppose we want to calculate their letter grade associated with their final score.

mutate with case_when()

Create letter_grade column that includes the calculated letter grade based on the score variable.

.tiny[

student_grades |>
  mutate(letter_grade = case_when(
    score >= 90 ~ "A",
    score >= 80 ~ "B",
    score >= 70 ~ "C",
    score < 70 ~ "F"
  ))
## # A tibble: 9  4
##   student subject    score letter_grade

## 5 B       literature    78 C           
## 6 B       PE            55 F           
## 7 C       math          12 F           
## 8 C       literature    96 A           
## 9 C       PE            57 F

Working with text data

The printed data3 table or data frame shows text data as chr.

data3
## # A tibble: 4  3
##   variable1 variable2 diagnosis              
##   <chr>     <chr>     <chr>                  
## 1 Name 1    SSN 1     <NA>                   
## 2 Name 2    SSN 2     <NA>                   
## 3 Name 3    SSN 3     Hypertension           
## 4 Name 4    SSN 4     End-stage renal disease

Again, text data in R is formally referred to as character type. In other programming languages, text data type is commonly referred to as string (or string type). Within the core tidyverse packages, the stingr package is the package designed for manipulating and processing text data.

Let us take a step back: basic R data structures

Many ways to store character data in R outside data frame / tables:

string1 <- "This is a single string"

string_vector <- c("This is string 1", "String 2 is brat!", 
                   "3rd String")

Example you already saw me creating Tables in R with text data earlier:

tibble::tribble(
       ~variable1, ~variable2, ~diagnosis,
      "Name 3",      "SSN 3", "Hypertension",
      "Name 4",     "SSN 4", "End-stage renal disease"  
  )
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   variable1 variable2 diagnosis              
##   <chr>     <chr>     <chr>                  
## 1 Name 3    SSN 3     Hypertension           
## 2 Name 4    SSN 4     End-stage renal disease

Let us take a step back: basic R data structures

Single vs Double Quotes

# Single quote works, but not best practice in R
string_v1 <- 'This is a single string'

# Double quote obviously works. Best practice over single quote.
string_v2 <- "This is a single string"

Combining strings: Combining Names with sep argument

str_c() accepts multiple variables/columns and allows you to combine string variables. note that inside str_c(), sep = has been added to indicate that you want a space between all the variables you want to combine together.

Let us combine the names into a single full name column: .tiny[

names_emails_list |>
  mutate(full_name = str_c(first_name, middle_name, last_name, sep = " ")) |>
  relocate(full_name)

Raw Strings

There are special characters that are directly illegal in R when creating strings.

For example, you cant just directly use the double quote symbol inside a string in R.

# an attempt you might be tempted to create:
example_text <- "This is a "test" of illegal special characters"
## Error: <text>:2:29: unexpected symbol
## 1: # an attempt you might be tempted to create:
## 2: example_text <- "This is a "test
##                                ^

Raw Strings

Figure 2. A real life example of text data from Twitter with a double quote symbol.



Figure 3. A real life example of how a real-world text data is represented in R.

In other words, test and treat from the Tweet in Figure 2 is represented within string in R as \"test and treat\".

In R, \" and similar work around are called escape characters.

Raw Strings: Escape Characters

Escape Characters in R:

  1. Backslash: \\
  2. New Line (Line Break): \n
  3. Tab: \t
  4. Single quote (): \'
  5. Double quote (): \"

Topic Indicators

It is often useful to create an indicator variable to indicate whether or not a text contains a topic of interest. For this analysis, let us focus on analyzing the contents of the headline variable.

Suppose you are a political scientist studying the news coverage of then-President Trump, and you want analyze a subset of related news headline.

Topic Indicators

We can create an indicator variable to indicate whether a string variable mentioned a topic of interest. The example use of str_detect() below is an example where we are asking R to analyze the headline column for its contents. If Trump is mentioned, str_detect returns a logical value (TRUE, FALSE).

Note: regex("trump", ignore_case = TRUE) is the pattern to detect. This slightly complicated format where we specify ignore_case = TRUE is going to detect Trump, trump, TRUMP, and other permutations.

.tiny[

news_headlines_v2 <- news_headlines |>
  mutate(trump_mentioned = str_detect(headline, regex("trump", ignore_case = TRUE))) |>
  relocate(trump_mentioned)

head(news_headlines_v2)
## # A tibble: 6  7
##   trump_mentioned datetime              headline url   teaser feed_name feed_url
##   <lgl>           <chr>                 <chr>    <chr> <chr>  <chr>     <chr>   
## 1 FALSE           July 18, 2017 at 03: 9-year- http Tyler abc7ny.c http://
## 2 FALSE           July 18, 2017 at 03: 10-year http The C abc7ny.c http://
## 3 FALSE           July 18, 2017 at 04: 10-year http A 10- abc7ny.c http://
## 4 FALSE           July 18, 2017 at 04: America http Al Bl abc7ny.c http://
## 5 FALSE           July 18, 2017 at 04: 12-year http Daphn abc7ny.c http://
## 6 FALSE           July 18, 2017 at 04: Exclusi http In an abc7ny.c http://

]

Topic Indicators

Example Descriptive Analysis:

.tiny[

news_headlines_v2 |>
  group_by(trump_mentioned) |>
  summarise(counts = n())
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   trump_mentioned counts
##   <lgl>            <int>
## 1 FALSE             9358
## 2 TRUE               387
# Extra to those who know base R (beyond the scope of this course)
# If you don't want to use this, use simple math in R: 387/(9358+387)
news_headlines_v2$trump_mentioned |>
  table() |>
  prop.table()
## 
##      FALSE       TRUE 
## 0.96028733 0.03971267

]

Insight: Out of the 9745 news headlines from ABC7 from New York City, roughly 387 (or 4%) mentioned Trump.

Topic Indicators

trump_mentioned_headlines <- news_headlines_v2 |>
